I"ì<p><a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/biological-reward-systems-are-malleable">Dopamine codes for (unexpected) reward</a> in <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/beliefs-are-gates-into-the-body-s-biochemistry">the body proper</a>. The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concepts-are-like-rooms">concept</a> of reward is a mental representation presumably supported by a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neural-substrate-of-social-interaction-enables-neurophysiological-turing-test">neural substrate</a>. A rewarding experience is <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/phenomenological-transparency-underpins-affordances">phenomenal</a>. The three flavors of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/representationism-in-cognition-is-adaptationism-in-evolution">representations</a> seem to perfectly overlap with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mind-mind-problem-decouples-cognition-and-experience">the components of the mind-mind problem</a>.</p>
